{
  "texts": [
    "This leads me to conclude that ai-systems cannot, once their ethical tensions on a local level are resolved, simply be considered a positive contribution in healthcare and medical settings, but that they must also be considered, at least from an ethical perspective, as a potential new global health issue which is in urgent need of further analysis and critical reflection.",
    "Ai-systems in healthcare and medicine-a characterisationThe use of ai-systems in healthcare and medicine Automated systems in healthcare and medicine are not a recent phenomenon but can rather be traced back to the 1950s [42,55] \"[…] when physicians made the first attempts to improve their diagnoses using computer-aided programs\" [55, p. 2].",
    "Nowadays, when we speak of automation, ai-systems immediately come to mind.",
    "With the increasing availability of enormous amounts of digital data and the growing computational power of modern computers, we are experiencing an exponential upsurge of different ai-systems (e.g.",
    "machine learning systems, deep learning systems, natural language processing systems) in society in general and in healthcare and medicine in particular [55,65].This upsurge is accompanied by an explosion of research on concepts, developments, testing, and implementation of ai-systems in different healthcare and medical domains across the world [42,48,54,55]."
  ]
}